response:
```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Potentiometer -> Attenuator -> AntiAliasFilter -> Buffer -> DAQ;

    Attenuator -> NotchFilter [label="To Attenuate\n50 and 60 Hz"];
    NotchFilter -> Attenuator [label="After Attenuation"];
}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer: The potentiometer is used as an angular position sensor. It converts the mechanical angle of the pendulum into a corresponding electrical voltage. Its resistance varies linearly with the angle of the pendulum within the range of 45 to 135 degrees.

Attenuator: This block reduces the voltage range from the potentiometer to match the accepted input range of the DAQ. Since the DAQ can only accept +/- 7 V and the potentiometer is powered by a +/- 10 V source, the attenuator ensures that the maximum voltage does not exceed the DAQ input voltage limits.

Notch Filter: This block is particularly designed to attenuate the frequencies around 50 and 60 Hz, which could be induced by power line interference. This is a critical requirement for ensuring clean signal acquisition.

Anti-Alias Filter: An anti-aliasing filter is used to remove high-frequency components that could cause aliasing when the signal is sampled by the DAQ at 1000 samples per second. It is typically a low-pass filter with a cutoff frequency set just below half of the sampling rate (Nyquist frequency) to satisfy the sampling theorem.

Buffer: The buffer is an amplifier with a high input impedance and low output impedance. It is used to prevent loading effects on the previous stages and to ensure proper signal transmission to the DAQ without loss or distortion. It acts as an isolation stage between the analog signal conditioning and the DAQ's analog-to-digital converter (ADC).

DAQ: The Data Acquisition System (DAQ) digitizes the conditioned analog signal from the pendulum's potentiometer for further processing and analysis. The DAQ is set to sample at a rate of 1000 samples per second, as per the project requirement.
```

